<section id="the-problem">
  <h2>1. The Real Problem</h2>
  <p>Most beginners treat affiliate links like regular hyperlinks — paste them in and hope for clicks. But affiliate links carry a psychological burden that normal links don't: the reader knows you'll earn money if they click. That awareness changes everything.</p>
  <p>The click rate depends on three things: where the link appears (placement), what surrounds it (context), and whether the reader trusts you (trust). Get any one wrong and the link dies.</p>
  <Callout type="info">
    <strong>Key insight:</strong> A link placed in the wrong context converts at 0.1%. The same link placed in the right context converts at 5–10%. Placement and context matter more than the product itself.
  </Callout>
</section>

<section id="placement">
  <h2>2. Link Placement That Works</h2>
  <p>Where you put the link determines whether anyone sees it. The best-performing placements follow a pattern: link after value, not before it.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll">
  <table>
    <tr><th>Placement</th><th>Click Rate</th><th>Why</th></tr>
    <tr><td>After a detailed explanation</td><td>High</td><td>Reader has context and is ready to act</td></tr>
    <tr><td>In a comparison table</td><td>High</td><td>Reader is actively evaluating options</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Mid-paragraph inline</td><td>Medium</td><td>Interrupts flow; feels promotional</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Bare at the bottom</td><td>Low</td><td>Reader has already decided to leave</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Popup or overlay</td><td>Very low</td><td>Triggers ad blindness and distrust</td></tr>
  </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highest-converting placement is after you've solved the reader's problem and the link feels like a natural next step — not a interruption.</p>
</section>

<a href="https://olspacademy.com/c/profitandprivilege" class="quote-banner" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer sponsored">
  <p>&ldquo;Discover the tools and training that can open the next chapter in your online marketing journey.&rdquo;</p>
</a>

<section id="context">
  <h2>3. Context Over Link</h2>
  <p>The words around your link matter more than the link text itself. "Click here" converts terribly. "I tested this tool for 3 months and here's what happened" converts well — because it gives the reader a reason to click that isn't just "buy something."</p>
  <p>Every affiliate link should be wrapped in a micro-story: what you did, what happened, and why the reader might want the same result. The link is the conclusion of that story, not the opening line.</p>
</section>

<section id="trust">
  <h2>4. Trust Before Clicks</h2>
  <p>Readers click links from people they trust. Trust comes from three sources: transparency (disclosing the affiliate relationship), competence (proving you know the topic), and consistency (showing up regularly with useful content).</p>
  <Callout type="warn">
    <strong>Hard rule:</strong> Never hide the fact that a link is an affiliate link. Disclosure builds trust; hiding it destroys it. Reddit communities and FTC guidelines both require clear disclosure.
  </Callout>
  <p>The fastest way to build trust is to provide genuine value without asking for anything in return. When you eventually include an affiliate link, the reader already trusts your judgment.</p>
</section>

<section id="technical">
  <h2>5. Technical Mistakes</h2>
  <p>Some clicks never happen because of technical issues:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Link cloaking that triggers spam filters.</strong> Raw affiliate URLs look suspicious. Use a clean redirect through your own domain.</li>
    <li><strong>Broken links.</strong> Programs change URLs. Check your links monthly.</li>
    <li><strong>Links that open in the same tab.</strong> Always use <code>target="_blank"</code> so the reader doesn't lose your page.</li>
    <li><strong>Mobile-unfriendly placement.</strong> Links too close together on mobile get fat-fingered or ignored.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Fix these first — they're the easiest wins and cost nothing.</p>
</section>

