<section id="faq">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <FaqItem question="How many affiliate links should I put in a single article?">
    <p>Start with 2–3 well-placed links rather than 10 scattered ones. Each link should have a clear reason to exist. More links dilute trust and trigger ad blindness. One link per major section is a good rule of thumb.</p>
  </FaqItem>
  <FaqItem question="Should I use text links or button links?">
    <p>Text links embedded naturally in your content typically outperform button links for affiliate marketing. Buttons look like ads and trigger ad blindness. Text links that are part of a helpful sentence feel like recommendations, not promotions.</p>
  </FaqItem>
  <FaqItem question="How long should I wait before expecting clicks?">
    <p>If you've fixed placement, context, and trust, give it 2–4 weeks for the changes to take effect. Traffic needs to flow through the updated content, and readers need time to build trust with your newer, more helpful approach.</p>
  </FaqItem>
  <FaqItem question="Does the product affect click rate?">
    <p>Less than you think. A well-placed link to a mediocre product will get more clicks than a poorly-placed link to a great product. Fix your placement and context first — the product choice is secondary.</p>
  </FaqItem>
  <FaqItem question="Should I disclose affiliate links in the article itself?">
    <p>Yes. A simple sentence like "This post contains affiliate links — I earn a commission if you purchase through them at no extra cost to you" placed near the first link builds trust and meets FTC requirements. Transparency converts better than concealment.</p>
  </FaqItem>
  <FaqItem question="What's the average click-through rate for affiliate links?">
    <p>For well-placed links in relevant content, 2–5% is realistic. For poorly placed links with no context, 0.1% or less is common. The difference is entirely in placement and context, not the product.</p>
  </FaqItem>
  <FaqItem question="Can I fix low clicks without creating new content?">
    <p>Yes. Update your existing articles: move links to better positions, add context around them, and improve the trust signals. Most of the time, optimizing existing content outperforms creating new content.</p>
  </FaqItem>
</section>

